<p><b>Blood alcohol content</b> (<b>BAC</b>), also called <b>blood alcohol =
concentration</b> or <b>blood alcohol level</b>, is a measurement of <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alcohol_intoxication" title=3D"Alcohol i=
ntoxication">alcohol intoxication</a> used for legal or medical purposes.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-Med2019_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Blood_alcohol_content#cite_note-Med2019-1"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=20
</p><p>BAC is expressed as mass of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Alcohol_(drug)" title=3D"Alcohol (drug)">alcohol</a> per volume of blood. =
In US and many international publications, BAC levels are written as a perc=
entage such as 0.08%, i.e. there is 0.8 grams of alcohol per liter of blood=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Med2019_1-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blood_alcohol_content#cite_note-Med2019-1"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-BAC_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Blood_alcohol_content#cite_note-BAC-2"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In differen=
t countries, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drunk_driving_law=
_by_country" title=3D"Drunk driving law by country">maximum permitted BAC w=
hen driving</a> ranges from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Li=
mit_of_detection" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Limit of detection">limit =
of detection</a> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zero_tolerance" =
title=3D"Zero tolerance">zero tolerance</a>) to 0.08% (0.8 <abbr title=3D"g=
rams per liter">g/L</abbr>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blood_alcohol_content#cite_note-3"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-BAC_2-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blood_alcohol_content#cite_note-BAC-2"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> BAC=
 levels above 0.40% (4 g/L) can be potentially fatal.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Me=
d2019_1-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blo=
od_alcohol_content#cite_note-Med2019-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Units_of_measurement">Units=
 of measurement</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DBlood_alcohol_content&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit =
section: Units of measurement"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edits=
ection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>BAC is generally defined as a fraction of weight of alcohol per volume o=
f blood, with an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SI_coherent_deriv=
ed_unit" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"SI coherent derived unit">SI cohere=
nt derived unit</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kilogram_pe=
r_cubic_metre" title=3D"Kilogram per cubic metre">kg/m<sup>3</sup></a> or e=
quivalently grams per liter (g/L). Countries differ in how this quantity is=
 normally expressed. Common formats are listed in the table below. For exam=
ple, the US and many international publications present BAC as a percentage=
, such as 0.05%. This would be interpreted as 0.05 grams per deciliter of b=
lood. This same concentration could be expressed as 0.5=E2=80=B0 or 50&nbsp=
;mg% in other countries.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blood_alcohol_content#cite_note-4"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup>
</p>
