<p>It is also possible to use other units. For example, in the 1930s Widmar=
k measured alcohol and blood by mass, and thus reported his concentrations =
in units of g/kg or mg/g, weight alcohol per weight blood. Blood is denser =
than water and 1 mL of blood has a mass of approximately 1.055 grams, thus =
a mass-volume BAC of 1 g/L corresponds to a mass-mass BAC of 0.948 mg/g. Sw=
eden, Denmark, Norway, Finland, Germany, and Switzerland use mass-mass conc=
entrations in their laws,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Jones2011_5-9" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blood_alcohol_content#cite_no=
te-Jones2011-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> but this distinction is often skipped over in pu=
blic materials,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blood_alcohol_content#cite_note-16"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> im=
plicitly assuming that 1 L of blood weighs 1 kg.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blood_alcohol_con=
tent#cite_note-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pharmacokinetics" title=
=3D"Pharmacokinetics">pharmacokinetics</a>, it is common to use the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amount_of_substance" title=3D"Amount of s=
ubstance">amount of substance</a>, in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Mole_(unit)" title=3D"Mole (unit)">moles</a>, to quantify the dose. As =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Molar_mass" title=3D"Molar mas=
s">molar mass</a> of ethanol is 46.07 g/mol, a BAC of 1 g/L is 21.706 mmol/=
L (21.706 mM).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blood_alcohol_content#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
