<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"By_training">By training</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBlood_alcohol_=
content&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: By traini=
ng"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></s=
pan></div>
<p>If individuals are asked to estimate their BAC, then given accurate feed=
back via a breathalyzer, and this procedure is repeated a number of times d=
uring a drinking session, studies show that these individuals can learn to =
discriminate their BAC, to within a mean error of 9&nbsp;mg/100 mL (0.009% =
BAC).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-40" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Blood_alcohol_content#cite_note-40"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The ability =
is robust to different types of alcohol, different drink quantities, and dr=
inks with unknown levels of alcohol. Trained individuals can even drink alc=
oholic drinks so as to adjust or maintain their BAC at a desired level.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-41" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Blood_alcohol_content#cite_note-41"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>40<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Training the ability =
does not appear to require any information or procedure besides breathalyze=
r feedback, although most studies have provided information such as intoxic=
ation symptoms at different BAC levels. Subjects continue to retain the abi=
lity one month after training.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-42" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blood_alcohol_content#cite_note-42"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>41<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Post-mortem">Post-mortem</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBlood_alcohol_=
content&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Post-mort=
em"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></s=
pan></div>
<p>After fatal accidents, it is common to check the blood alcohol levels of=
 involved persons. However, soon after death, the body begins to <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Putrefaction" title=3D"Putrefaction">putrefy=
</a>, a biological process which produces ethanol. This can make it difficu=
lt to conclusively determine the blood alcohol content in autopsies, partic=
ularly in bodies recovered from water.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-43" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blood_alcohol_content#cite_=
note-43"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>42<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-44" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blood_alcohol_content#cite_note-44"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p><sup id=3D"cite_ref-45" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Blood_alcohol_content#cite_note-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-46" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blood_=
alcohol_content#cite_note-46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>45<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For instance, following the 1975 =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moorgate_tube_crash" title=3D"Moor=
gate tube crash">Moorgate tube crash</a>, the driver's kidneys had a blood =
alcohol concentration of 80&nbsp;mg/100&nbsp;mL, but it could not be establ=
ished how much of this could be attributed to natural decomposition.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-47" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Blood_alcohol_content#cite_note-47"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>46<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Newer research has shown=
 that vitreous (eye) fluid provides an accurate estimate of blood alcohol c=
oncentration that is less subject to the effects of decomposition or contam=
ination.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-48" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Blood_alcohol_content#cite_note-48"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>47<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Legal_limits">Legal limits<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBlood_alcoho=
l_content&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Legal =
limits"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span=
></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drunk_driving_law_by=
_country" title=3D"Drunk driving law by country">Drunk driving law by count=
ry</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Map_of_European_countries_by_maximum_blood_al=
cohol_level.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.w=
ikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e0/Map_of_European_countries_by_maxi=
mum_blood_alcohol_level.svg/330px-Map_of_European_countries_by_maximum_bloo=
d_alcohol_level.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"300" height=3D"229" cl=
ass=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"680" data-file-height=3D"520"></=
a><figcaption>Map of Europe showing countries' blood alcohol limits as defi=
ned in g/dL for the general population</figcaption></figure>
<p>For purposes of law enforcement, blood alcohol content is used to define=
 intoxication and provides a rough measure of impairment. Although the degr=
ee of impairment may vary among individuals with the same blood alcohol con=
tent, it can be measured objectively and is therefore legally useful and di=
fficult to contest in court. Most countries forbid operation of motor vehic=
les and heavy machinery above prescribed levels of blood alcohol content. O=
peration of boats and aircraft is also regulated. Some jurisdictions also r=
egulate bicycling under the influence. The alcohol level at which a person =
is considered legally impaired to drive varies by country.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Test_assumptions">Test assu=
mptions</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBloo=
d_alcohol_content&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit section=
: Test assumptions"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Extrapolation">Extrapolatio=
n</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBlood_alco=
hol_content&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: Extr=
apolation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</s=
pan></span></div>
<p>Retrograde <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Extrapolation" title=
=3D"Extrapolation">extrapolation</a> is the mathematical process by which s=
omeone's blood alcohol concentration at the time of driving is estimated by=
 projecting backwards from a later chemical test. This involves estimating =
the absorption and elimination of alcohol in the interim between driving an=
d testing. The rate of elimination in the average person is commonly estima=
ted at 0.015 to 0.020&nbsp;grams per deciliter per hour (g/dL/h),<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-49" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Blood_alcohol_content#cite_note-49"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>48=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> although again this can var=
y from person to person and in a given person from one moment to another. M=
etabolism can be affected by numerous factors, including such things as bod=
y temperature, the type of alcoholic beverage consumed, and the amount and =
type of food consumed.
</p><p>In an increasing number of states, laws have been enacted to facilit=
ate this speculative task: the blood alcohol content at the time of driving=
 is legally presumed to be the same as when later tested.  There are usuall=
y time limits put on this presumption, commonly two or three hours, and the=
 defendant is permitted to offer evidence to rebut this presumption.<sup cl=
ass=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;"=
>[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" ti=
tle=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs reference=
s to reliable sources. (September 2025)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</s=
up>
</p><p>Forward extrapolation can also be attempted. If the amount of alcoho=
l consumed is known, along with such variables as the weight and sex of the=
 subject and period and rate of consumption, the blood alcohol level can be=
 estimated by extrapolating forward. Although subject to the same infirmiti=
es as retrograde extrapolation=E2=80=94guessing based upon averages and unk=
nown variables=E2=80=94this can be relevant in estimating BAC when driving =
and/or corroborating or contradicting the results of a later chemical test.=
<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:No_original_research" titl=
e=3D"Wikipedia:No original research"><span title=3D"The material near this =
tag possibly contains original research. (September 2025)">original researc=
h?</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Metabolism">Metabolism</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBlood_alcohol_co=
ntent&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit section: Metabolism=
"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></spa=
n></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pharmacology_of_etha=
nol#Pharmacokinetics" title=3D"Pharmacology of ethanol">Pharmacology of eth=
anol =C2=A7&nbsp;Pharmacokinetics</a></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pharmacokinetic" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Pharmacokinetic">pharmacokinetics</a> of ethanol are w=
ell characterized by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ADME" tit=
le=3D"ADME">ADME</a> acronym (absorption, distribution, metabolism, excreti=
on). Besides the dose ingested, factors such as the person's <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Total_body_water" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D=
"Total body water">total body water</a>, speed of drinking, the drink's nut=
ritional content, and the contents of the stomach all influence the profile=
 of blood alcohol content (BAC) over time. Breath alcohol content (BrAC) an=
d BAC have similar profile shapes, so most forensic pharmacokinetic calcula=
tions can be done with either. Relatively few studies directly compare BrAC=
 and BAC within subjects and characterize the difference in pharmacokinetic=
 parameters. Comparing arterial and venous BAC, arterial BAC is higher duri=
ng the absorption phase and lower in the postabsorptive declining phase.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-Jones2019_50-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Blood_alcohol_content#cite_note-Jones2019-50"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Highest_levels">Highest lev=
els</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBlood_al=
cohol_content&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14" title=3D"Edit section: Hi=
ghest levels"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]=
</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_deaths_through_a=
lcohol" title=3D"List of deaths through alcohol">List of deaths through alc=
ohol</a></div>
<p>According to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guinness_World_Rec=
ords" title=3D"Guinness World Records">Guinness World Records</a>, the 2013=
 incident where a BAC of 1.374% (13.74 g/L) was recorded is the highest BAC=
 recorded in a human who survived the ordeal.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:2_51-0" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blood_alcohol_c=
ontent#cite_note-:2-51"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>50<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
